Evolution and Tensions
Ethnopharmacology has shifted from purely descriptive roots (mid-20th century) toward more rigorous, technology-integrated models. Key tensions include:
Reductionist (single-molecule) vs. Holistic (multi-component) approaches.
Natural sciences dominance vs. greater inclusion of social/cultural methods. 

sciencedirect.com

Ethical concerns around bioprospecting and equitable partnerships.

Consensus guidelines (e.g., from Michael Heinrich and others) stress minimal methodological standards: accurate taxonomy, transparent ethnomedical data, and robust phytochemical profiling. 

sciencedirect.com

Overall, the field operates across multiple paradigms simultaneously, with increasing emphasis on integration and systems thinking. This pluralism is a strength, allowing ethnopharmacology to contribute to both cultural preservation and innovative therapeutics in a globalized context. For doctoral-level work, researchers often combine paradigms (e.g., ethnographic documentation followed by network pharmacology validation)."

